[metadata] {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/app/project/docs/architecture/adr/002-event-driven-architecture.md", "content": "```markdown\n# Architecture Decision Record: 002 — Event-Driven Architecture\n\n* **Status** : Accepted  \n* **Date**   : 2024-06-08  \n* **Stakeholders** :  \n  * Product: VP Product, Lead Product Manager  \n  * Engineering: Chief Architect, Platform Tech-Lead, Backend Guild  \n  * Operations: SRE Lead, DevOps Lead  \n  * Compliance & Security: CISO, Risk Officer  \n\n---\n\n## 1. Context  \n\nFortiLedger360 is expected to ingest and react to a high volume of fine-grained security events (e.g., *“Tenant A requests deep vulnerability scan”*, *“Cluster-X exceeds 75 % CPU for 90 s”*, *“Config-drift detected on Edge-Node-17”*).  \nTraditional synchronous request/response workflows (REST or RPC) impose tight coupling, limited extensibility, and waterfall-style failure domains.  \n\nKey platform requirements:  \n\n* **Scalability** – Burst to > 250 K events/s while maintaining < 200 ms P95 processing latency.  \n* **Extensibility** – Add a new service (e.g., `ComplianceAuditor`) with zero downtime.  \n* **Fault Isolation** – Failure in `BackupNode` must **not** block `AlertBroker`.  \n* **Observability** – Every state transition must emit traceable, structured audit logs.  \n* **Multi-tenant Guardrails** – Tenants demand isolated QoS & configurable SLAs.  \n\nThese constraints steer us toward **Event-Driven Architecture (EDA)** built around an **asynchronous, durable, high-throughput event bus**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Decision  \n\nWe will implement an Event-Driven Architecture in which:  \n\n1. **Domain events** are first-class citizens.  \n2. **Producers** (e.g., API Gateway, ConfigManager) publish immutable events onto a **shared, partition-keyed event bus** (Kafka-compatible; currently **NATS JetStream** in PoC).  \n3. **Consumers** (e.g., Scanner, Metrics, AlertBroker) subscribe to event topics and process them **idempotently**.  \n4. **Commands** and **Queries** are explicitly separated (CQRS).  \n5. **gRPC** remains the inter-service transport for low-latency, **request/reply workflows** (e.g., control-plane sync), but **all business workflows** flow through the event bus to preserve auditability.  \n6. **Exactly-once** semantics are guaranteed at the *application* level via outbox pattern + deduplication headers (ulid event-id).  \n7. A **reference C++ client** wraps JetStream to enforce encryption, tracing, and retry policies.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Consequences  \n\n### Positive  \n* Loose coupling → Horizontal service agility.  \n* Native scalability via topic sharding & consumer groups.  \n* Natural audit log & replay capability → compliance win.  \n* Enables decoupled failure handling and resiliency patterns (DLQ, back-pressure).  \n\n### Negative / Trade-offs  \n* Added operational complexity: JetStream clusters, topic ACLs, and schema evolution.  \n* Higher learning curve for developers unfamiliar with EDA patterns.  \n* Latency overhead vs. sync RPC (≈ 5–15 ms per hop).  \n\n### Follow-ups  \n* Implement **Schema Registry** (Apache Avro) + compatibility gates in CI.  \n* Define **tenant partition-key strategy** for QoS isolation.  \n* Provide **SDKs** (Go, Rust, C++) with consistent observability hooks.  \n\n---\n\n## 4. Reference Implementation (C++)\n\nBelow is an excerpt from `messaging/EventBus.hpp` showcasing the thin, opinionated wrapper around NATS JetStream.  \nIt demonstrates publishing a `SecurityScanInitiated` event and consuming with **exactly-once** semantics.\n\n```cpp\n#pragma once\n#include <nats/nats.h>\n#include <chrono>\n#include <future>\n#include <iostream>\n#include <stdexcept>\n#include <string>\n#include <string_view>\n#include <unordered_set>\n\n/**\n * @brief FortiLedger360 :: EventBus\n *\n * Opinionated, thread-safe JetStream wrapper providing:\n *   • Schema-validated payloads (JSON/Avro)\n *   • mTLS enforcement\n *   • Automatic ULID-based idempotency keys\n *   • Structured tracing (OpenTelemetry)\n */\nclass EventBus {\npublic:\n    explicit EventBus(std::string_view natsUrl,\n                      std::chrono::milliseconds timeout = std::chrono::seconds(5))\n        : url_{natsUrl}, reqTimeout_{timeout}\n    {\n        natsOptions_Create(&opts_);\n        natsOptions_SetURL(opts_, url_.c_str());\n        // TODO: configure mTLS: natsOptions_SetSecureContext(...)\n        auto s = natsConnection_ConnectTo(&conn_, opts_);\n        if (s != NATS_OK) {\n            throw std::runtime_error(\n                \"EventBus: unable to connect to NATS: \" + std::string(natsStatus_GetText(s)));\n        }\n        // JetStream context\n        s = natsConnection_JetStream(&js_, conn_, nullptr);\n        if (s != NATS_OK) {\n            throw std::runtime_error(\n                \"EventBus: unable to create JetStream context: \" + std::string(natsStatus_GetText(s)));\n        }\n    }\n\n    ~EventBus()\n    {\n        if (js_)  natsJetStream_Destroy(js_);\n        if (conn_) natsConnection_Destroy(conn_);\n        if (opts_) natsOptions_Destroy(opts_);\n    }\n\n    struct PublishAck {\n        std::string stream;\n        std::string domain;\n        uint64_t    sequence{};\n    };\n\n    // Publish JSONArray/Avro serialised bytes; async by default\n    auto publish(std::string_view subject,\n                 std::string_view payload,\n                 std::string_view msgId /* ULID */,\n                 bool synchronousAck = false) -> std::future<PublishAck>\n    {\n        // Headers: idempotency + trace\n        natsMsg* msg{};\n        natsMsg_Create(&msg, subject.data(), nullptr, payload.data(), payload.size());\n        natsMsgHeader_Set(msg, \"Nats-Msg-Id\", msgId.data());\n        // TODO: inject OpenTelemetry trace headers\n\n        return std::async(std::launch::async, [=] {\n            jsPubAck* ack{};\n            auto s =\n                natsJetStream_PublishMsg(js_, &ack, msg,\n                                         synchronousAck ? NATS_JETSTREAM_PUB_SYNCAWAIT : 0);\n            natsMsg_Destroy(msg);\n\n            if (s != NATS_OK) {\n                throw std::runtime_error(\"publish failed: \" + std::string(natsStatus_GetText(s)));\n            }\n\n            PublishAck r{ack->Stream, ack->Domain, ack->Seq};\n            jsPubAck_Destroy(ack);\n            return r;\n        });\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * Subscribe with at-least-once semantics.  \n     * Application layer is responsible for idempotency using the message ULID.\n     */\n    void subscribe(std::string_view subject,\n                   const std::function<void(const natsMsg*)>& handler,\n                   std::string durableName = \"\")\n    {\n        natsSubscription* sub{};\n        jsSubOpts opts{};\n        jsSubOpts_Init(&opts);\n        opts.Durable = durableName.empty() ? nullptr : durableName.c_str();\n        opts.AckPolicy           = js_AckExplicit;\n        opts.MaxDeliver          = 5; // retry/poison message threshold\n        opts.IdleHeartbeat       = 30 * 1'000'000'000ULL; // 30s\n\n        auto s = natsJetStream_Subscribe(&sub, js_, subject.data(), nullptr,\n                                         internalMsgCb, const_cast<void*>(static_cast<const void*>(&handler)), &opts);\n        if (s != NATS_OK) {\n            throw std::runtime_error(\"subscribe failed: \" + std::string(natsStatus_GetText(s)));\n        }\n        activeSubs_.emplace(sub);\n    }\n\nprivate:\n    static void internalMsgCb(natsConnection*, natsSubscription*, natsMsg* msg, void* closure)\n    {\n        auto* userCb = reinterpret_cast<std::function<void(const natsMsg*)>*>(closure);\n        try {\n            (*userCb)(msg); // userland processing\n            natsMsg_Ack(msg); // explicit ack\n        } catch (const std::exception& ex) {\n            std::cerr << \"[EventBus] handler exception: \" << ex.what() << '\\n';\n            natsMsg_Nak(msg, nullptr, 0); // negative ack → redelivery\n        }\n        natsMsg_Destroy(msg);\n    }\n\n    std::string                     url_;\n    std::chrono::milliseconds       reqTimeout_{};\n    natsOptions*                    opts_{};\n    natsConnection*                 conn_{};\n    natsJetStreamContext*           js_{};\n    std::unordered_set<natsSubscription*> activeSubs_;\n};\n```\n\nUsage sample for the `Scanner` service:\n\n```cpp\n#include \"messaging/EventBus.hpp\"\n#include <ulid/ulid.hpp> // hypothetical ULID lib\n\nint main() {\n    EventBus bus{\"tls://nats.internal.fortiledger360.io:4222\"};\n\n    // Producer side: announce that a scan has started.\n    auto ulid = ulid::generate();\n    bus.publish(\n        \"security.scan.initiated\",\n        R\"({\"tenant\":\"acme\",\"cluster\":\"edge-a1\",\"depth\":\"deep\"})\",\n        ulid)\n        .get(); // wait for ack\n\n    // Consumer side: listen for completion\n    bus.subscribe(\"security.scan.completed\", [](const natsMsg* msg) {\n        std::string payload{natsMsg_GetData(msg), natsMsg_GetDataLength(msg)};\n        // TODO: parse JSON & persist results\n        std::cout << \"[Scanner] Received scan.completed: \" << payload << '\\n';\n    }, \"scanner-completed-durable\");\n\n    // Block main thread (demo purposes)\n    std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::hours(24));\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. References  \n\n* NATS JetStream – https://docs.nats.io/nats-concepts/jetstream  \n* “Building Event-Driven Microservices” – Adam Bellemare  \n* CNCF CloudEvents Specification – https://github.com/cloudevents/spec  \n* OpenTelemetry for C++ – https://opentelemetry.io/docs/instrumentation/cpp/  \n\n```", "numLines": 239, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 239}}

1→```markdown
     2→# Architecture Decision Record 003  
     3→## Title: Standardise on gRPC over mTLS inside an Envoy-based Service Mesh
     4→
     5→* Status: **Accepted**  
     6→* Date: 2024-06-11  
     7→* Supersedes / Amends: None  
     8→* Authors: Platform & Runtime Chapter  
     9→
    10→---
    11→
    12→### 1. Context  
    13→FortiLedger360 consists of ~40 micro-services distributed across five bounded-context
    14→layers.  The initial prototype relied on *REST/JSON* for inter-service communication and
    15→used a bespoke DNS+Consul mechanism for discovery.  As we approach General Availability
    16→and a target throughput of 35 K cross-service calls per second, the following pain-points
    17→have become critical:
    18→
    19→* High per-call latency caused by HTTP/1.1 + JSON (≈ 1.7 ms serialisation cost alone).  
    20→* No first-class streaming semantics — mandatory for continuous vulnerability scans.  
    21→* Ad-hoc security: hand-rolled JWTs, static API keys, no mutual-TLS.  
    22→* Operational blind-spots: we cannot uniformly enforce retries, circuit-breakers, or
    23→  trace context propagation.  
    24→
    25→### 2. Decision  
    26→We will:
    27→
    28→1. Adopt **gRPC (HTTP/2)** as the canonical RPC protocol between internal services.  
    29→2. Mandate **mutual-TLS** using the platform’s Certificate-Authority for every gRPC call.  
    30→3. Deploy all workloads **behind Envoy sidecars** (managed by Istio¹) to realise a
    31→   zero-trust **Service Mesh** featuring:  
    32→   * mTLS termination & rotation  
    33→   * out-of-the-box retries, circuit-breaking, deadline and back-off policies  
    34→   * distributed tracing via OpenTelemetry → Jaeger  
    35→   * L7 metrics and rate-limiting  
    36→4. Generate C++ stubs via `protoc --cpp_out` for low-latency services written in C++17
    37→   (Scanner, Metrics, BackupNode).  Java/Kotlin, Go and Rust services will continue to
    38→   use language-appropriate gRPC bindings.  
    39→
    40→¹ Istio can be swapped with Consul Connect or Kuma if future requirements dictate.
    41→
    42→### 3. Consequences  
    43→
    44→* (+) 4–6× faster intra-cluster calls (binary Protobuf, header compression, multiplexed
    45→  streams).  
    46→* (+) Uniform security posture: every hop is authenticated & encrypted.  
    47→* (+) Mesh provides traffic-shaping without code changes.  
    48→* (±) Incremental learning curve: teams must master Protobuf, gRPC error-model, Envoy.  
    49→* (–) Additional sidecar footprint (~80 MiB RAM / pod) and control-plane overhead.  
    50→
    51→---
    52→
    53→## 4. Reference Implementation (C++ 17)
    54→
    55→Below is a distilled yet functional excerpt taken from the *Scanner* bounded context.  
    56→The code compiles with **grpc 1.61+**, **OpenSSL 3** and enables *sanitizers* in `CMakeLists.txt`.
    57→
    58→### 4.1 `scanner.proto`
    59→
    60→```proto
    61→syntax = "proto3";
    62→
    63→package fortiledger360.scanner.v1;
    64→
    65→option java_package = "com.fortiledger360.scanner.v1";
    66→option go_package   = "fortiledger360/scanner/v1;scannerpb";
    67→
    68→// Command Pattern — invokes an asynchronous scan.
    69→message InitiateSecurityScanRequest {
    70→  string tenant_id   = 1;
    71→  string resource_id = 2; // VM, container, or k8s-namespace
    72→  enum Depth {
    73→    DEPTH_UNSPECIFIED = 0;
    74→    QUICK             = 1;
    75→    DEEP              = 2;
    76→  }
    77→  Depth depth = 3;
    78→}
    79→
    80→message InitiateSecurityScanResponse {
    81→  string scan_id = 1;
    82→}
    83→
    84→// Observer/Strategy Pattern — stream incremental findings.
    85→message ScanFinding {
    86→  string vulnerability_id = 1;
    87→  string severity         = 2;
    88→  string description      = 3;
    89→  int64  detected_at_ms   = 4;
    90→}
    91→
    92→service SecurityScanner {
    93→  rpc InitiateSecurityScan (InitiateSecurityScanRequest)
    94→        returns (InitiateSecurityScanResponse);
    95→
    96→  // Server-side streaming for real-time dashboards.
    97→  rpc StreamFindings (google.protobuf.StringValue) // scan_id
    98→        returns (stream ScanFinding);
    99→}
   100→```
   101→
   102→### 4.2 `security_scanner_server.cpp`
   103→
   104→```cpp
   105→/**
   106→ * @file security_scanner_server.cpp
   107→ * @brief gRPC server for the SecurityScanner bounded context.
   108→ *
   109→ * Build:
   110→ *   $ cmake -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=RelWithDebInfo
   111→ *   $ cmake --build build -j
   112→ */
   113→
   114→#include <csignal>
   115→#include <filesystem>
   116→#include <fstream>
   117→#include <grpcpp/ext/proto_server_reflection_plugin.h>
   118→#include <grpcpp/grpcpp.h>
   119→
   120→#include "scanner.grpc.pb.h"
   121→
   122→using fortiledger360::scanner::v1::SecurityScanner;
   123→using fortiledger360::scanner::v1::InitiateSecurityScanRequest;
   124→using fortiledger360::scanner::v1::InitiateSecurityScanResponse;
   125→using fortiledger360::scanner::v1::ScanFinding;
   126→
   127→namespace fs = std::filesystem;
   128→
   129→static std::atomic_bool g_terminate{false};
   130→
   131→class SecurityScannerServiceImpl final : public SecurityScanner::Service
   132→{
   133→public:
   134→    grpc::Status InitiateSecurityScan(grpc::ServerContext* context,
   135→                                      const InitiateSecurityScanRequest* request,
   136→                                      InitiateSecurityScanResponse* response) override
   137→    {
   138→        if (request->tenant_id().empty() || request->resource_id().empty())
   139→        {
   140→            return grpc::Status(grpc::StatusCode::INVALID_ARGUMENT,
   141→                                "tenant_id and resource_id must be set");
   142→        }
   143→
   144→        // Naïve UUID — replace with a robust generator in prod.
   145→        const std::string scan_id = "scan-" + std::to_string(++scan_counter_);
   146→        response->set_scan_id(scan_id);
   147→
   148→        // Off-load heavy scan to a dedicated thread-pool.
   149→        std::thread{&SecurityScannerServiceImpl::performScan, this,
   150→                    scan_id, *request}.detach();
   151→
   152→        return grpc::Status::OK;
   153→    }
   154→
   155→    grpc::Status StreamFindings(grpc::ServerContext* context,
   156→                                const google::protobuf::StringValue* scan_id_val,
   157→                                grpc::ServerWriter<ScanFinding>* writer) override
   158→    {
   159→        const std::string scan_id = scan_id_val->value();
   160→        absl::ReaderMutexLock lk(&findings_mu_);
   161→        auto it = findings_.find(scan_id);
   162→        if (it == findings_.end())
   163→        {
   164→            return grpc::Status(grpc::StatusCode::NOT_FOUND, "Unknown scan_id");
   165→        }
   166→
   167→        for (const auto& finding : it->second)
   168→        {
   169→            if (!writer->Write(finding))
   170→            {
   171→                // Client aborted.
   172→                break;
   173→            }
   174→        }
   175→        return grpc::Status::OK;
   176→    }
   177→
   178→private:
   179→    void performScan(std::string scan_id, InitiateSecurityScanRequest request)
   180→    {
   181→        // Simulate scan workflow. In reality this would call ClamAV, Trivy, etc.
   182→        std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::milliseconds(250));
   183→
   184→        ScanFinding f;
   185→        f.set_vulnerability_id("CVE-2023-1234");
   186→        f.set_severity("HIGH");
   187→        f.set_description("Sample buffer-overflow vuln");
   188→        f.set_detected_at_ms(
   189→            std::chrono::duration_cast<std::chrono::milliseconds>(
   190→                std::chrono::system_clock::now().time_since_epoch()).count());
   191→
   192→        {
   193→            absl::WriterMutexLock lk(&findings_mu_);
   194→            findings_[scan_id].push_back(std::move(f));
   195→        }
   196→
   197→        // Persist to event-bus for further processing (omitted).
   198→    }
   199→
   200→    std::atomic_uint64_t scan_counter_{0};
   201→    absl::Mutex findings_mu_;
   202→    std::unordered_map<std::string, std::vector<ScanFinding>> findings_ ABSL_GUARDED_BY(findings_mu_);
   203→};
   204→
   205→static void handleSignal(int)
   206→{
   207→    g_terminate.store(true);
   208→}
   209→
   210→static std::string readFile(const fs::path& p)
   211→{
   212→    std::ifstream ifs(p, std::ios::binary);
   213→    if (!ifs)
   214→        throw std::runtime_error("Unable to open " + p.string());
   215→    return {std::istreambuf_iterator<char>(ifs), {}};
   216→}
   217→
   218→int main(int argc, char* argv[])
   219→{
   220→    const fs::path kCertDir   = "/etc/fortiledger360/certs/";
   221→    const fs::path kCertFile  = kCertDir / "server.crt";
   222→    const fs::path kKeyFile   = kCertDir / "server.key";
   223→    const fs::path kCaFile    = kCertDir / "ca.crt";
   224→
   225→    grpc::SslServerCredentialsOptions::PemKeyCertPair pkcp{
   226→        readFile(kKeyFile), readFile(kCertFile)};
   227→    grpc::SslServerCredentialsOptions ssl_opts;
   228→    ssl_opts.pem_key_cert_pairs.push_back(pkcp);
   229→    ssl_opts.pem_root_certs = readFile(kCaFile);
   230→    ssl_opts.client_certificate_request =
   231→        GRPC_SSL_REQUEST_AND_REQUIRE_CLIENT_CERTIFICATE_AND_VERIFY;
   232→
   233→    std::shared_ptr<grpc::ServerCredentials> creds =
   234→        grpc::SslServerCredentials(ssl_opts);
   235→
   236→    SecurityScannerServiceImpl service;
   237→
   238→    grpc::EnableDefaultHealthCheckService(true);
   239→    grpc::reflection::InitProtoReflectionServerBuilderPlugin();
   240→
   241→    grpc::ServerBuilder builder;
   242→    builder.AddListeningPort("0.0.0.0:50051", creds);
   243→    builder.RegisterService(&service);
   244→    std::unique_ptr<grpc::Server> server(builder.BuildAndStart());
   245→
   246→    std::signal(SIGINT, handleSignal);
   247→    std::signal(SIGTERM, handleSignal);
   248→
   249→    std::cout << "SecurityScanner gRPC server started on :50051 (mTLS enabled)\n";
   250→    while (!g_terminate.load())
   251→        std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::seconds(1));
   252→
   253→    server->Shutdown();
   254→    server->Wait();
   255→    std::cout << "SecurityScanner gracefully terminated.\n";
   256→    return 0;
   257→}
   258→```
   259→
   260→### 4.3 `security_scanner_client.cpp`
   261→
   262→```cpp
   263→/**
   264→ * @file security_scanner_client.cpp
   265→ * @brief Example envoy-injected client that calls the scanner via mTLS.
   266→ */
   267→
   268→#include <grpcpp/grpcpp.h>
   269→#include "scanner.grpc.pb.h"
   270→
   271→using fortiledger360::scanner::v1::SecurityScanner;
   272→using fortiledger360::scanner::v1::InitiateSecurityScanRequest;
   273→using fortiledger360::scanner::v1::InitiateSecurityScanResponse;
   274→
   275→static std::shared_ptr<grpc::Channel> makeSecureChannel()
   276→{
   277→    grpc::SslCredentialsOptions ssl_opts;
   278→    ssl_opts.pem_root_certs = ""; // Envoy sidecar performs TLS => plaintext loopback
   279→    return grpc::CreateChannel("127.0.0.1:15001", grpc::InsecureChannelCredentials());
   280→}
   281→
   282→int main()
   283→{
   284→    auto channel = makeSecureChannel();
   285→    std::unique_ptr<SecurityScanner::Stub> stub = SecurityScanner::NewStub(channel);
   286→
   287→    InitiateSecurityScanRequest req;
   288→    req.set_tenant_id("tenant-42");
   289→    req.set_resource_id("k8s-namespace-prod");
   290→    req.set_depth(InitiateSecurityScanRequest::DEPTH::InitiateSecurityScanRequest_Depth_DEEP);
   291→
   292→    grpc::ClientContext ctx;
   293→    InitiateSecurityScanResponse resp;
   294→    grpc::Status status = stub->InitiateSecurityScan(&ctx, req, &resp);
   295→
   296→    if (!status.ok())
   297→    {
   298→        std::cerr << "RPC failed: " << status.error_message() << '\n';
   299→        return EXIT_FAILURE;
   300→    }
   301→    std::cout << "Scan ID: " << resp.scan_id() << '\n';
   302→    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
   303→}
   304→```
   305→
   306→---
   307→
   308→### 5. Operational Topology
   309→
   310→```mermaid
   311→flowchart TD
   312→    subgraph Service Mesh (Istio)
   313→        SC[SecurityScanner] <-- gRPC/mTLS --> MN[MetricsNode]
   314→        SC <-- gRPC/mTLS --> BN[BackupNode]
   315→        SC <-- gRPC/mTLS --> AB[AlertBroker]
   316→    end
   317→    classDef svc fill:#0f5e9c,stroke:#fff,stroke-width:2px,color:#fff;
   318→    class SC,MN,BN,AB svc;
   319→```
   320→
   321→Envoy sidecars transparently enforce per-method time-outs, automatic retries (`retryOn:
   322→5xx,connect-failure,refused-stream`) and distributed traces exported to the
   323→OpenTelemetry Collector.
   324→
   325→---
   326→
   327→### 6. Risk Mitigation & Future Work  
   328→
   329→* Blue-green roll-outs validated in a staging mesh before prod promotion.  
   330→* Pen-tests scheduled to validate certificate rotation and downgrade attack resilience.  
   331→* Evaluate HTTP/3 + gQUIC once officially supported by gRPC-C++.  
   332→
   333→---
   334→
   335→### 7. Rejected Alternatives
   336→
   337→| Alternative | Rationale for Rejection |
   338→|-------------|-------------------------|
   339→| Continue with REST/JSON + Custom TLS | Latency & missing streaming semantics outweighed familiarity benefits. |
   340→| Apache Thrift | We already depend on gRPC in the Java pipeline; doubling infra was unjustified. |
   341→| ZeroMQ | Lack of built-in authN/Z, difficult to operate at scale in Kubernetes. |
   342→
   343→---
   344→
   345→This ADR is **accepted** and effective immediately.  All new internal service
   346→interfaces **must** be defined in Protobuf and exposed via gRPC; legacy endpoints
   347→are slated for migration over the next two quarters.
   348→```

